      <div class="msgContentFrame">It totally depends on the relationship.  I know families that just have a join bank account.  I also know families where due to various factors they have separate bank accounts.  In one case creating separate bank account probably saved the marriage.  I'd imagine that for people who like to buy things and easily spend money, separate bank accounts would be very wise to avoid the idea that one person is working while the other person takes advantage of that regardless of the actual reality in the situation. <br /> <br />I don't think this is at all taboo though, I've certainly never thought about it that way. <br /> <br /><div class="msgQuote"><div class="source">Quote:</div><div class="orig">I'm going to have to say that I don't understand the point of keeping a separate account from your husband/wife. <br /> <br />If you love/trust someone enough to marry them, then you shouldn't have to think twice before letting them have access to your money.</div></div>Even in a very stable loving/trusting marriage, there are still currents that you have to be sensitive to.  It's still a normal everyday relationship.  I don't think it's very often about access or trust, but rather the feeling of inequality or being taken advantage of.  It might be a subtle thing that people in the relationship easily discard as being not true most of the time, but in the middle of the argument or fight, it could make things worse.  Again it depends totally on the people involved. <br /> <br /><i><span class="sm">Edited, Nov 21st 2010 11:12pm by Xsarus </span></i><div class="msgSig"><div class="msgSigBar sm">----------------------------</div><span class="sm">01001001 00100000 01001100 01001001 01001011 01000101 00100000 01000011 01000001 01001011 01000101 <br />You'll always be stupid, you'll just be stupid with more information in your brain</span></div></div>
