      <div class="msgContentFrame">Separate accounts can be dangerous as well. My uncle and aunt had separate accounts for their entire marriage (25-odd years). My uncle was a day trader and always made a healthy amount - he paid for the mortgage, car payments, and utilities, while my aunt handled the day-to-day expenses like groceries, cleaning supplies, clothing, etc. As the recession came about, it just came to light that my uncle had been using equity on the house to try and make increasingly risky trades, and many of them were busting. My aunt had no idea he was doing this until he came to her a few months ago and admitted they might lose the house. Now my uncle is out of a job and my aunt is supporting both of them while trying to bail out the back payments on the mortgage on her teacher's salary. If they had been more open about finances, and particularly if they had at least one joint account for the mortgage, car, and other large, consistent expenses, they would probably be a lot better off. <br /> <br />Now, that said, if and when I get married that's how I plan to do it. I'd have a joint account for those mandatory expenses, and a separate for my own smaller expenses (video games, vacations, nights out, etc).  <br /> <br />I also think a retirement account should be joint, just so both parties can make sure they're contributing the proper amount. This assumes both people are working, obviously.<div class="msgSig"><div class="msgSigBar sm">----------------------------</div>News Reporter for the ZAM Network. <br /> <br />WoW - Naoki - level 66 Mage on Skywall <br />Aureliano the Insane - level 80 Druid on Sen'Jin <br />Junkboxing - level 80 Rogue on Sen'Jin <br />Nathanos - level 80 Blood Knight on Sen'Jin</div></div>
