      <div class="msgContentFrame">When Ray was in the Navy, it was much easier for everything to be joint and both of our pay got deposited into that account.  I handled all the bills because it was easier that way.  Ray was on deployment and I was stateside to handle everything.  After everything was paid, I transferred half of whatever was leftover into Ray's separate account and kept the other half in my separate account.  We still had access to each other's separate accouts but never raided them.  I'd just let Ray know how much bills were, how much fun money there was and he was OK with that system. <br /> <br />It's still the same system even now that Ray's retired from the military.  When either of us get paid, I go over the income and bills that get paid and we figure out the leftover for savings/investment and how much is fun money.  That's our haggling time because Ray's got his eye on a new 52&quot; LED TV and I have my eye on a cruise to the Bahamas next year. <br /> <br />ETA:  I do have to say that it does take an inordinate amount of trust for spouses to trust one another to handle joint accounts together.  I've seen this scenario go south many times as a paralegal. <br /> <br /><i><span class="sm">Edited, Nov 22nd 2010  2:54pm by Thumbelyna </span></i><div class="msgSig"><div class="msgSigBar sm">----------------------------</div><div class="msgQuote"><div class="source">Guenny wrote:</div><div class="orig"> And don't bother replying, Varus, because I'm not going to go in a circle with you about how I'm a white trash liberal because I'm not a slave to the almighty dollar. I'm a @#%^ing stoner hippie who just wants justice, peace, love, unicorns, and double-rainbows and sh*t. In fact, I've never once made fun of the fact that you're gay, just because I'm so accepting of alternative lifestyles and all that jazz. @#%^philia and abortions for everyone!</div></div></div></div>
