      </div>
      <div class="msgContentFrame"><div class="msgQuote"><div class="source">Timelordwho wrote:</div><div class="orig"><div class="msgQuote"><div class="source">Uglysasquatch wrote:</div><div class="orig"><div class="msgQuote"><div class="source">Bardalicious wrote:</div><div class="orig">I think it is pretty stupid to draw an account until it hits even close to 0. <br /> <br />Anyone who actually does that isn't managing their money well at all.  Stop buying things you cant afford.</div></div>Not all people have enough money to not be living pay cheque to pay cheque. When did you start channeling Varus type stupidity?</div></div> <br /> <br />People not living paycheck to paycheck should also not have large sums in their checking account. <br /> <br />It's really just a place to float cash until it's needed in an investment or purchase.</div></div> <br /> <br />What qualifies as a &quot;large sum&quot; kinda varies, doesn't it? Unless you are anal about managing your account balances, it's better to err on the side of having a bit too much in there than too little. At a minimum, you should have enough in your checking account to cover 2 months worth of normal expenses. That should allow you to handle sudden costs and unforeseen problems. You can put the extra into a higher interest bearing account (theoretically that should be enough to handle 6 months worth of expenses), and the extra beyond that should be put into longer term investment. <br /> <br />The idea being that you have enough in your &quot;normal&quot; account to cover most things that come along, certainly enough to deal with two people both spending money at the same time and not realizing the other is doing so. And you have enough so that if there's a job loss, you can still survive on your savings without having to pull money out of your investments (for which there may be penalties or timing issues) long enough to get another job. <br /> <br />Obviously, this assumes you are *not* living paycheck to paycheck. But I don't think it's unreasonable at all to maintain $6-10k in your regular checking account for use when you need it. And if either of you are spending sufficient amounts to empty your account because of that, there's something else going wrong. <br /> <br /> <br />As to managing a joint account, I suppose that's going to depend on the couple (duh!). I would think that the best approach would be to direct deposit both incomes into a single shared joint checking account. Then make decisions about how to budget that money. Obviously, household bills should come right out of the joint account. Extra money can be split between individual accounts and some kind of investment strategy. But IMO the first purpose of the money earned by a couple should go to providing the things that both of them rely on (home, car(s), food, utilities). How they want to deal with the rest is pretty negotiable. <br /> <br /> <br />Honestly, the bigger issue usually isn't with joint accounts, but with credit cards. That's usually where one person's bad spending habits screw them both up. Because at the end of the day, whether the accounts are joint or not really doesn't matter. Both members are equally financially responsible for the actions of them both. If one person racks up thousands of dollars of credit card bills, it's kinda silly to quibble over who's account is going to pay the bill.<div class="msgSig"><div class="msgSigBar sm">----------------------------</div><div class="msgQuote"><div class="source">King Nobby wrote:</div><div class="orig">More words please</div></div></div></div>
      <div class="msgFtFrame">
